  "text": ", the refractive index increases at 600 nm are 0.05 and 0.18, respectively. These values can be related to the measurements on turtle eyes by Ives et al. [CITATION_1] . They estimated that in the red, at around 650 nm, the refractive index of clear, yellow and red oil droplets is 1.48, 1.55 and 1.69, respectively. This means that the carotenoids increased the refractive index of the yellow and red oil droplets by 0.07 and 0.21, values similar to the 0.05 and 0.18 of the carotenoid contributions calculated for the yellow and red oil droplets of birds. The oil droplets are surrounded by the watery photoreceptor cytoplasm, the refractive index of which will be around 1.34. Assuming that the transparent oil droplets of birds, such as those of turtle [CITATION_2] , have in the red a refractive index 1.48, the refractive indices of the yellow and red oil droplets will be 1.48 þ 0.05 ¼ 1.53 and 1.48 þ 0.18 ¼ 1.66, so that the refractive index contrast with the cytoplasm for the T-, Y-and R-droplets becomes 0.14, 0.19 and 0.32. All oil droplets thus will act as a spherical lens, but their optical power will be quite different.",
